snippet.textDisplay:
I wonder if there are any other very large people out there? I am 5 years post cancer treatment and very inactive for years. I’m 100 pounds overweight. BC(before cancer) this would have been a piece of cake(ugh cake). Now I made it only about halfway. I was shaky right away and cried over how unfit and unhappy I am. I will try the 20 minute beginner video tomorrow then hope to come back to this.
Post chemo I have developed hypothyroidism, type 2 diabetes, and possibly an undiagnosed autoimmune disease. I am also always extremely low on magnesium, also due to chemo. So I can cramp up as much as 20 times a day. Even little neck and cheek muscles cramp. I almost don’t think I could be in worse shape, but I can sit, and stand for a few minutes, so I know that’s not true.

snippet.textDisplay: I want to thank you from the bottom of my heart. I havent been doin yoga for 4 months and i always regretted it. i always had excuses for not doing Yoga with Adriene (i started with the dedicated serie in last august). At the first downward dog, I felt reallycrappy - everything felt so stiff and not right, i could only hold on for seconds. I felt so terrible and continued anyway.. Then at the 2nd Downward Dog it felt pretty Okay! it wasnt as bad as the first time?! and as the training goes on I felt even better and stronger. So I'm here wantin to share my experience and realized that there a many people having similar feelings and thoughts like me.. and are still continueing. I can't put in words of how much thankful I am and how u saved my day today as I originally felt so much selfhatred today. Thank you for  bringing us together, for your kindness and sharing this yoga lessons for free. It means so much. See you tomorrow :D

snippet.textDisplay: Hi Adriene (and all the lovely folks here!) I wanted to say that I am very excited about these thirty days of home practice, and I am so grateful to have found this space. 2019 was one of the most challenging of my life, and while I'm under no illusions that all can be fixed at once, finding YWA and slowing growing a daily practice is one of the most valuable discoveries I made that year, and that I take with me into this next year, and decade. Practicing at home, but still with a feeling of connectivity to this community has been immensely helpful when I have felt isolated yet unable to leave my own home. It has helped me not to fear looking inwards, but being open to what I might find there, and to deal with whatever I encounter. Thank you for guiding me, and this community, with such grace and humour (and an adorable dog!), it is incredible valuable work that you do. Happy New Year everyone!

snippet.textDisplay: I had a rough start to this practice; I could not keep my head on the mat. But by the time we were halfway through, I'd fallen into a much more familiar and comfortable yoga headspace, and I'm so grateful. My body definitely hurt, since I haven't done any practice for... weeks now, and everything was cracking and twanging, but at least I was waking it up, and hopefully the next days will tune it all. Still figuring out how the idea of 'home' resonates with me at this weird point in my life, but that can be part of the journey along with my body. Glad today's root canal didn't keep me from doing this. Excited for the days ahead!
